<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-168-284  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 168 284.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Andrew Seybold's Outlook on Professional Computing  March 20 1989v7 n8 p13(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Scanners and OCR begin to come of age. (scanning technology)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Cox, Thomas.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Scanners, together with OCR software, can produce text files byreading paper documents directly into computers.andP;  Throughput iscomparable to a 300 bps modem and, although somewhat slow,scanning can eliminate the rekeying and proofreading of documents,enhancing productivity.andP;  There are several categories of scanners,each of which handles physical documents differently; overhead andflatbed models are probably the best.andP;  Scanners for personalcomputers generally scan at a resolution of 300 dots per inch,limiting their usefulness for documents with small writing.andO;Higher resolution scanners require a computer system with morememory, more disk space and a faster processor.andP;  Setting upscanners can be time consuming and cumbersome, and finding goodOCR software is difficult.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     ScanningOptical Character ReadersOffice AutomationImage GenerationDocument Preparation.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>